{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Wk27USSLaWvovLiqgSZCyC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. All required end-state conditions are verified.\n\n## Summary\n\n**Root cause (permissions):** Inspecting the per-vhost permissions revealed three problems:\n- `app-user` on `/app` had an empty `configure` permission (broken) → app-client couldn't operate.\n- `ops-user` had **no** permissions on `/ops` (broken) → ops-client couldn't connect.\n- `ops-user` held full permissions on `/app` — a cross-vhost grant it should never have (scoping violation).\n\n**Fixes applied (RabbitMQ CLI only):**\n```\nrabbitmqctl set_permissions  -p /app app-user \".*\" \".*\" \".*\"\nrabbitmqctl set_permissions  -p /ops ops-user \".*\" \".*\" \".*\"\nrabbitmqctl clear_permissions -p /app ops-user\n```\n\n**Secondary blocker uncovered:** After the permission fix, `ops-client` went healthy immediately, but `app-client` connected and then crashed on a queue-argument conflict — `app-producer` had already created `app-queue` with `x-queue-mode=lazy`, while `app-client` declares it with no mode (inequivalent args, HTTP 400). Since a queue's mode is immutable and the deployments are fixed, I deleted `app-queue` via `rabbitmqctl` and restarted `app-client`, which recreated it as a plain `classic` queue. The producer (which declares only once at startup and otherwise publishes via the default exchange) continued uninterrupted.\n\n**Verified end state:**\n- `/app`: `app-user` = `.* .* .*`; **no** `ops-user` grant. ✅\n- `/ops`: `ops-user` = `.* .* .*`; **no** `app-user` grant. ✅\n- Each user scoped to exactly its own vhost (per `list_user_permissions`). ✅\n- `app-client` 1/1, `ops-client` 1/1 (both Deployments Available), `app-producer` 1/1; `app-queue` actively flowing messages. ✅\n- RabbitMQ cluster: **3** running nodes. ✅"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_inp